<task id="060" project="ai-sprk-chat-workspace-companion">
  <metadata>
    <title>Wire QuickActionChips and Context Fetch into SprkChat.tsx</title>
    <phase>2E-Wiring: Enhanced Pane Integration</phase>
    <status>completed</status>
    <estimated-hours>3</estimated-hours>
    <dependencies>040, 041, 031</dependencies>
    <blocks>081</blocks>
    <tags>frontend, typescript, react, shared-library, fluent-ui</tags>
    <rigor-hint>FULL</rigor-hint>
    <rigor-reason>Modifies SprkChat.tsx to fetch context mapping endpoint and mount QuickActionChips; integrates SlashCommandMenu state management; 6+ steps</rigor-reason>
    <parallel-group>E</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Update `SprkChat.tsx` to: (1) fetch the context-mappings/analysis endpoint when analysisId is available in context, (2) mount `QuickActionChips` above the input bar with actions from the endpoint response, (3) mount `SlashCommandMenu` with system + playbook commands, and (4) ensure chips update when playbook changes.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    SPAARKE platform developer. Expert in React 19 state management and SprkChat architecture. Read SprkChat.tsx thoroughly before modifying.
  </role>

  <goal>
    SprkChat.tsx fetches context mapping, renders QuickActionChips above input (hidden when pane &lt; 350px via component), and provides SlashCommandMenu with dynamic commands from playbook capabilities.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      SprkChat.tsx is the main orchestrator component in the shared library. It already manages sessions, playbook selection, and message sending. This task adds context-driven enrichment: fetch the analysis context mapping endpoint (using the analysisId from props/URL params), populate QuickActionChips, and build the slash command registry. The fetching should use the existing BFF API client pattern in the component.
    </background>
    <relevant-files>
      <file>src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/components/SprkChat/SprkChat.tsx</file>
      <file>src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/components/SprkChat/SprkChatInput.tsx</file>
      <file>src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/components/SprkChat/hooks/useChatPlaybooks.ts</file>
      <file>src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/components/SprkChat/QuickActionChips.tsx</file>
      <file>src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/components/SlashCommandMenu/SlashCommandMenu.tsx</file>
    </relevant-files>
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="spec-FR-08">Quick-action chips MUST update when playbook changes — re-fetch or re-filter on playbook change</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-012">Context fetch MUST use the BFF API client (auth token) — not direct fetch without auth</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">Chips are populated from context mapping endpoint inlineActions (first 4)</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>projects/ai-sprk-chat-workspace-companion/spec.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-012-shared-components.md</file>
    </files>
    <patterns>
      <pattern name="SprkChat API calls" location="src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/components/SprkChat/hooks/useChatPlaybooks.ts">
        Read useChatPlaybooks.ts to understand how the BFF API is called from the shared library. Follow the same pattern for the context mapping fetch.
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">Read SprkChat.tsx and useChatPlaybooks.ts to understand API call patterns and props interface</step>
    <step order="2">Add analysisId to SprkChat props (optional — only present in Analysis Workspace context)</step>
    <step order="3">Add useEffect in SprkChat.tsx: when analysisId is present, fetch GET /api/ai/chat/context-mappings/analysis/{analysisId}</step>
    <step order="4">Store response in state: contextMapping (AnalysisChatContextResponse | null)</step>
    <step order="5">Re-fetch when activePlaybookId changes (add to useEffect dependency array)</step>
    <step order="6">Mount QuickActionChips above SprkChatInput: pass contextMapping?.inlineActions.slice(0,4), onChipClick calls sendMessage with chip action</step>
    <step order="7">Pass containerRef to QuickActionChips for width detection</step>
    <step order="8">Pass contextMapping?.inlineActions as dynamic commands to SlashCommandMenu (via useSlashCommands hook)</step>
    <step order="9">Build shared library; verify no type errors</step>
    <step order="10">Update TASK-INDEX.md: change task 060 status to ✅ completed</step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool name="npm">Build TypeScript/React</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <output type="code">src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/components/SprkChat/SprkChat.tsx</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">Given analysisId in props, when SprkChat mounts, then GET context-mappings/analysis endpoint is called.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Given context mapping returns 6 inline actions, when QuickActionChips renders, then only 4 chips are shown.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Given playbook changes, when new playbook is selected, then context mapping is re-fetched.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Shared library builds without TypeScript errors.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    The BFF API call needs an auth token — follow the exact same pattern as useChatPlaybooks.ts (it likely uses a fetch wrapper or React context that provides auth). Don't introduce a new fetching mechanism. If analysisId is not in props, skip the context fetch entirely (SprkChat works without it for non-analysis contexts). Keep the QuickActionChips chip-to-message formatting simple: chip click → send "[Quick Action: {chipLabel}]" message.
  </notes>

  <execution>
